cs.SI, cs.IR, cs.HC, cs.MM, cs.CL 

This paper discusses the usage of social networks in social media sites for information filtering and browsing. It involves analyzing data from Digg and Flickr to understand how users express their tastes and interests through social networks. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). The paper also involves information retrieval and human-computer interaction, which makes cs.IR (Information Retrieval) and cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) likely sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses multimedia content (e.g., photos on Flickr), which makes cs.MM (Multimedia) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves natural language processing (e.g., analyzing user-generated content), which makes cs.CL (Computation and Language) a less likely but still possible sub-category.
